This paper is likely to belong to the Information Retrieval (cs.IR) category as it deals with predicting booking probability and value at the traveler level, which is a central problem in computational advertising for vacation rental marketplaces. The paper also mentions the use of session logs as a data source, which is a common technique in IR research.

The paper also involves the use of deep and shallow neural networks, which suggests that it could belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) category. The use of embeddings and gradient boosting tree models further supports this.

The paper also mentions the use of natural language processing techniques, such as word embeddings, which suggests that it could belong to the Computational Linguistics (cs.CL) category.

The paper also involves the use of data analysis and modeling techniques, which suggests that it could belong to the Cybernetics (cs.CY) category.

Finally, the paper mentions the deployment of the proposed model into a production system, which suggests that it could belong to the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) category.
